For this example, will use the data made available through microbiome package. Data set from Halfvarson et al. Nature Microbiology 2, 2017 characterizes longitudinal fluctuations of human intestinal microbiota in Inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) subjects and compare it with those of healthy individuals. The authors use Illumina HiSeq 2000 for the V4 region with 515F/806RBC. This data was downloaded from Qiita and the Qiita study ID is 1629.

The data is already in phyloseq format. I will show how to load it and do the analysis. For your analysis, you will use the phyloseq object you created using the main tutorial.

Default function from SpiecEasi

Kindly run the following codes for getting edge values with positive and negative correlations.

#' get opt merge
#'
#' Get the optimal merge matrix StARS is run.
#'
getOptMerge <- function(est) {
    if (class(est) == "select" && est$criterion == "stars") {
        return(est$merge[[est$opt.index]])
    } else 
        stop("Run spiec-easi with criterion=\"stars\"")

}


getOptBeta <- function(est) {
    if (class(est) == "select" && est$method == "mb") {
        return(est$beta[[est$opt.index]])
    } else 
        stop("Run spiec-easi with method=\"mb\"")
}

#' sym beta
#' Symmetrize a beta (coefficient) matrix, ie. selected from MB neighborhood selection
#'
symBeta <- function(beta, mode='ave') {
    if (mode=='ave') {
        symbeta <- (beta+t(beta))/2
   } else if (mode == "maxabs") {
        upt <- Matrix::triu(beta)
        lot <- t(Matrix::tril(beta))
        suppressMessages(maxt <- pmax(abs(upt), abs(lot)))
        uptind <- Matrix::which(maxt == abs(upt))
        lotind <- Matrix::which(maxt == abs(lot))
        if (length(uptind != 0)) maxt[uptind] <- maxt[uptind]*sign(upt[uptind])
        if (length(lotind != 0)) maxt[lotind] <- maxt[lotind]*sign(lot[lotind])
        symbeta <-  maxt + t(maxt)
    } else if (mode == "upper") {
        upt <- Matrix::triu(beta)
        symbeta <-  upt + t(upt)
    } else if (mode == "lower") {
        lot <- Matrix::tril(beta)
        symbeta <- lot + t(lot)
    } else 
        stop ("mode not recognized")
    as(symbeta, 'symmetricMatrix')
}

SPIEC-EASI network reconstruction

This is a slow step and depending on the number of Genera, time will vary from few minutes to hours.

# In practice, use more repetitions
set.seed(12534)
net.c <- spiec.easi(otu.c, method='mb', icov.select.params=list(rep.num=50))
## Normalizing/clr transformation of data with pseudocount ...
## Inverse Covariance Estimation with mb ...
## Model selection with stars ...
## Done!
#please use more numebr of rep.num (99 or 999) the paraemters

Create graph object

n.c <- symBeta(getOptBeta(net.c))

colnames(n.c) <- rownames(n.c) <- colnames(otu.c)#you can remove this 

vsize <- log2(apply(otu.c, 2, mean))# value we may or may not be used as vertex.attribute

ibd.ig <- graph.adjacency(n.c, mode='undirected', add.rownames = TRUE, weighted = TRUE)

Assign color based on weights of correlation

#now color the edges based on their values 
E(ibd.ig)[weight > 0]$color<-"green" #positive values
E(ibd.ig)[weight < 0]$color<-"red"   #negative values

Set layout and plot simple network

More info on igraph layouts

#set layout
coords.ibd.ig = layout_with_fr(ibd.ig)

plot(ibd.ig, layout=coords.ibd.ig, vertex.size = 2, vertex.label.cex = 0.5)

convert data for better plotting.

hc.net <- asNetwork(ibd.ig)

Ggnet plot

set edge attributes

set.edge.attribute(hc.net, "color", ifelse(hc.net %e% "weight" > 0, "green", "red"))

Coloring and node size

Color the nodes based on Phylum affiliation.

Set the node size to log2 mean abundance.

phyla <- map_levels(colnames(otu.c), from = "Genus", to = "Phylum", tax_table(ibd.hc.g))
hc.net %v% "Phylum" <- phyla
hc.net %v% "nodesize" <- vsize

mycolors <- scale_color_manual(values = c("#a6cee3", "#1f78b4", "#b2df8a", "#33a02c","#fb9a99","#e31a1c","#fdbf6f","#ff7f00","#cab2d6","#6a3d9a","#ffff99","#b15928"))

Inferred microbial ecological networks

p1 <- ggnet2(hc.net, node.color = "Phylum", label = TRUE, node.size = "nodesize", size.legend = NULL,label.size = 4, edge.color = "color") +  guides(size = FALSE) + mycolors + ggtitle("Healthy Network")

Modularity in ecological networks

For information on different algorithms check igraph manual

ibd.comm <- ibd.ig
ibd.louvain <- cluster_louvain(ibd.comm, weights = NA)

print(ibd.louvain)
## IGRAPH clustering multi level, groups: 22, mod: 0.61
## + groups:
##   $`1`
##   [1] "Roseburia"
##   
##   $`2`
##   [1] "Dehalobacterium"
##   
##   $`3`
##   [1] "Anaerostipes"
##   
##   $`4`
##   + ... omitted several groups/vertices

We can see that there were 22 groups detected and the modularity of the network is 0.61. " Modularity >0.4 indicates that the partition produced by the modularity algorithm can be used to detect distinct communities within the network. It indicates that there are nodes in the network that are more densely connected between each other than with the rest of the network and that their density is noticeably higher than the graphs average (Newman, 2006)."

Network properties can be used to understand potential ecological realtions. Example Dynamics of bacterial community succession in a salt marsh chronosequence: evidences for temporal niche partitioning

Marine bacterial, archaeal and protistan association networks reveal ecological linkages

For more details check the article by Newman 2006

# simple plot 

V(ibd.comm)$community <- ibd.louvain$membership
pdf("ibd_healthy_modularity.pdf", height = 14, width = 16)
plot(ibd.comm, vertex.color=V(ibd.comm)$community, vertex.label.cex = 0.5, vertex.size = 5, asp = 0.9)
